> Potato dauphinoise is possibly the most luxurious and delicious invention on the planet (according to our chef Mimi). But this gratin is the slightly healthier version. Potatoes and broccoli combined with pancetta and cream, go hand in hand with some delicious sausages from our friends at Roaming Roosters, and with a side of honey glazed carrots, you can't go wrong!

Bring a large #pot of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} and pre-heat your #oven to 210 degrees.

Peel and chop your @potato{1} into roughly 2cm pieces and separate your @broccoli{1} into florets.

Add your chopped potato to your pot of boiling water and cook for ~{5%minutes} before adding your broccoli and cooking for a further ~{5%minutes}. Drain and leave in your #colander for ~{2%minutes}.

In the meantime, pull your @thyme{8} leaves off their stalks with your finger and thumb.

Peel and chop your @carrots{4} in half lengthways, then chop into batons about 1cm wide and the length of your index finger. Peel and cut your @red onion{2} in half through the root and slice thinly into half moon shapes. Grate your @mature cheddar cheese{8}.

Add @oil{1%tbsp} to a #frying pan on medium heat and add your @British smoked bacon lardons{1}. Cook for ~{4%minutes} or until crispy, then take the pan off the heat.

Pour your @double cream{2} into a #jug, add half your grated cheese and half your thyme leaves along with @Dijon mustard{1%tbsp} (or more if you like things very mustardy), @salt{1/2%tsp} and a really good grind of @pepper{}. Pop your drained broccoli and potatoes into an #ovenproof dish{}. Take the pancetta out of the pan and add this to the dish as well (leave the oil from the pancetta in the frying pan if you can). Pour over your cream mixture and top the whole thing with your remaining cheese, your @panko breadcrumbs{3} and another pinch of salt and pepper. Put your dish in the #oven on the top shelf to cook for ~{25-30%minutes} or until bubbly and brown on top.

In the meantime, pop your @sausages{8} on a #baking tray{} and put them in the #oven to cook for ~{25%minutes} as well. Add your carrots to a separate baking tray, drizzle over @oil{2%tbsp}, your @honey{1}, remaining thyme leaves, @salt{1/4%tsp} and a good grind of @pepper{}. Give the tray a good shake and put in the #oven to cook for ~{20-25%minutes}.

> If your oven only has two shelves, just put your carrot baking tray at the very bottom of the oven to cook.

Add @oil{1%tbsp} to the #frying pan you had your pancetta in (no need to wash!). Put on medium heat and add your onion along with @salt{1/4%tsp}, a good grind of pepper and @?sugar{1/2%tsp}. Cook for ~{10%minutes}, stirring occasionally until the onions have softened. Add your @balsamic vinegar{1} to the pan and cook for a further ~{10%minutes} on a very low heat. When the onions are soft and caramelised, put a #lid on the pan and leave to the side until everything else is ready.

When the gratin is brown and bubbling, the carrots are roasted and the sausages are cooked, get them all out of the #oven and serve on plates, with a spoonful of your caramelised onion on the side.